{{unreferenced|date=March 2009}}
'''Longfellow, Alden, & Harlow''' was the architectural firm of [[Alexander Wadsworth Longfellow, Jr.]] (1854<U+2013>1934) '''Frank E. Alden''' (1859<U+2013>1908) and '''Alfred B. Harlow''', (1857<U+2013>1927). The firm, successors to [[H. H. Richardson]], continued to provide structures in the [[Romanesque revival]] style established by Richardson.

The architects [[Frederick G. Scheibler, Jr.]] and [[Henry M. Seaver]] trained in the firm's office.

==Selected commissions==
*[[Edwin Abbot House]], 1889.
*[[Brattle Hall]], [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] (1889)
*[[Cambridge, Massachusetts City Hall]], in [[Richardsonian Romanesque]] style.
 
*[[J.A. Noyes House]], [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] (1894)
*[[Carnegie Building (Pittsburgh)]] (1895) The first steel-framed building in Pittsburgh.
*[[Carnegie Library of Homestead]], [[Munhall, Pennsylvania ]] (1896).
*[[Cloud Factory|Bellefield Boiler Plant]], Pittsburgh (1907), in Richardsonian Romanesque style.  Built to provide steam for the [[Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh|Carnegie Institute]].  
*[[Theodore Parker Church]], [[West Roxbury, Massachusetts]] (1890)
